The BNHBC molecule, like HBC-BCNU and NHBC-BCNU, plays a significant role in determining the HOMO energy level in the BNHBC-BCNU complex. However, BCNU plays an essential role in determining the LUMO energy level, as shown in Fig. 10(b). The distribution of HOMO and LUMO orbitals in the BNHBC-BCNU structure is in complete agreement with the PDOS plot depicted in Fig. 11
                        . Before and after the formation of a complex with a drug molecule, the trend of distribution of atomic charges in the BNHBC molecule is comparable to NHBC. There is a notable difference, though, in the partial charge of nitrogen atoms, which is more negative at about −0.98 |e|. The partial charge of boron atoms, on the other hand, is strongly positive at about 1.05 |e|, as expected (see Fig. 12
                        ).
